<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Shaman are adequate at melee. They'll never touch a real melee class in that area, but they can melee all the same. My shaman had pretty good ac between 14 and 34. I had a medley of banded, Cabilis scale, and Scaled Mystics armor. At 14, you can root and nuke, but it's sloppy at best. Most of my fights started with my best slow spell followed by my best DoT. Then, I'd just beat the monster to death. Sometimes, I found it better to let 1 DoT run it's course while the mob was rooted, the reapply the DoT, hit it with slow, then finally melee. This strategy worked fine for me every time. At 24, it just gets easier to do the same thing, or you can simply root and poison your target if you really don't like melee. At 29, things got much easier. I had about 680 ac at that point, a good slow spell, and haste. In most cases, I didn't even need to rely on my spells to do damage. I could melee a target to death...though a poison DoT always made things nicer. Most shamans that complain about a lack of melee ability are the ones who dress like druids and ignore ac. A shaman is able to wear heavier armor than druids, so they should take advantage of that. A high wis isn't all that important since we get a mana regen spell at 24, and mana regen is much more important that max mana. If you haven't yet invested much into your shaman, I suggest you run your ac up as high as you can, and not worry too much about wis until you have to. It really does make things much easier. Even if you choose not to melee when gaining exp, you should melee a little (maybe against low blues) just to keep your def skill maxed. That's free ac. You can't beat that with a stick. Shaman do not melee well, but with the right combination of spells, we can bring out target down close to our level so that both we and our opponent stink. Once we get 'em there, our damage spells can give us a nasty edge.
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
