<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Well, putting no points into wisdom is an extreme situation, and a very silly one.  Of course you had trouble.<P>And you knew he was talking about cannibalize, gimme a break.  And cannibalize does make your mana increase, or, regen. Same thing, whatever.<P>And using it doesn't always increase your downtime either; sometimes it decreases it.  <P>Anyway, to the original poster, I'd just say that you should melee at every opportunity, almost.  Keep your casting skills up, too, though, especially being careful not to let conjuration(your DOTs) get too far behind, or divination.  Most shamans let divination, especially, fall far behind.  Keep conj up by conjuring food and water over and over again until you want to scream; keep div up by using sense animals and true north for an hour or so every once in a while.  Casting skills max out at level x 5, plus an extra 5, and melee(for shamans) at level x 4 plus. <P>The reason I say keep melee up every chance you get is that you can increase casting skills in the ways I just mentioned, not by fighting.  Weapons skills and offense and defense ONLY go up by fighting.  You miss your chance, it's gone.  It's easy to get way behind, and most shamans do -- most get far behind in defense, and are only good at one weapon, usually the spear.<P>You're too powerful a character not to be well-rounded in everything.  You're a great tank when soloing, once the mob is slowed and you have a "quick" or "haste" spell on, and are all buffed out -- IF you wear lots and lots of AC gear.  You'll probably want to have plenty of wisdom/mana gear AND AC gear, and switch them in and out depending on the situation.  Even in your 40's and into your 50's, you can still do a LOT of melee damage.  Personally, at level 45 I melee like crazy, using a two-hand blunt, and never cast a DOT at all, and am almost never in danger.  I can do the same thing with a one-hand club or a spear, because I earned it by fighting up close and personal a lot.  I won't be able to do this after a while, because super-high level mobs are just too tough, but I'll be very glad at that point that I built up my skills before then, so I can take a hit, or land a spear or club or staff that fires off a spell into the hide of an enemy.  (What good is a good weapon if you can't land it, or don't have the AC to take a hit while you try?)<P>Anyone who doubts the value of defensive skill should remember that every increase in defense skill equals 2.5 AC.  The only way to increase defense skill is to melee and get hit.  You won't get hit enough in groups for it to matter, once you get beyond perhaps your 20's.  So you'll have to solo to keep your potential AC up, or you won't be nearly as tough as you could be.  And there's no sense not having high AC; there's not a character in the game who doesn't benefit by high AC.  <P>Solo and melee as much as you can while young, because it's much harder getting skill increases and still surviving after you level a bit--mobs become much tougher.  If you group a lot you will probably level much faster, but be weak or only good at one weapon.  If some nice weapon drops into your lap, you won't be able to use it except for the stats on it, and if something hits you, you're in real deep trouble real fast compared to someone who has put in the grunt work, meleeing his defense/AC up.<P>There's plenty of time for casting.  You'll rarely not have casting maxed or close to it.  Don't rush into the wisdom thing and get too hooked on casting; there will come a time when that's all you'll be doing.  Mix it up a little, and melee, and get those melee skills up before the mobs become so tough it's just too late.  You can't regret doing the right thing by your character.  Imagine the difference it would make having 50 more AC, and then go out and get it -- for free! -- by meleeing stuff.
</FONT>
