<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I have to disagree that shamans are not good at soloing until 49.  I solo all the time, and have at least a bit at most every level to my present level 45, and do it using mostly melee, to boot, and do it with only 120 wis, the rest all AC armor -- although I've used different armor/wis at different times.  <P>The argument that they can't do it EFFICIENTLY is a subset of the above argument, and more complicated than it seems.  The main reason it might seem inefficient is because it can require long downtimes.  That itself is complex and subject to a lot of variables dependent on yet other variables, so what is true for some may not be true for others.  In other words, soloing will be efficient for some, but not others.  I would argue that if it is not efficient for many people, that is more often than not because they have neglected certain aspects of their development and have come to pay the price.  Many shamans start on an irreversible spiral down to weakness.<P>If you are casting a lot of DOTs, you'll  need a lot of downtime to meditate your mana back up.  If you are casting a lot of heals because you get beat up a lot, also lots of downtime.  If you're not managing your pet right and have to heal him all the time, more downtime.<P>However, you might be casting a lot of DOTs and heals because your have poor weapons skills and poor armor and/or have poor defense/AC for your level and the level of mobs you are fighting, and simply are not tough enough to do any physical fighting; you might be relying on DOTs because you realistically have no other choice, given how you have thus far chosen to develop your character.  For most shamans, the latter will be the case.  Very few I ever bump into have their defense maxed, thereby maximizing their natural AC.  However, you can build up your AC through simple hard work.  <P>If you do keep your AC up, you will need substantially fewer heals.  Personally, I never cast one.  I don't even keep heal memmed when soloing.  I just keep chloroplast on.  You'll also need far fewer DOTs.  Therein lies the potential efficiency, once you're fully prepared.<P>As an example from my own experience, when I first noted, at level 39, that I had gotten far behind in my melee skills and defense/AC, I spent a couple of weeks selling SOW potions like mad so I could buy some better AC armor.  Then I went to the Overthere and started soloing to fix myself up.  <P>I pulled with winter's roar (230 DD) and dragged the mob back to my pet, who was far enough away that by the time the mob caught up to the pet and me, I had successfully cast a slow spell.  I cast the venom of snake DOT.  Then the pet and I meleed.  I got beat up pretty good, and sometimes the pet did too, because my weapons skills could have been higher and caused more aggro.  I cast the VOS DOT a second time.  Sometimes I won handily, sometimes I barely survived.  I died a couple of times.<P>After a while, my weapons skills shot way up, as did offense, and, most importantly, defense, which increased my AC.  My defense went up more than 20 points, giving me more than 50 extra AC.  (By now, it has gone up far more.)  This made all the difference in the world.  Now, I pull with my lowest mana DD, just to get some aggro going, or sometimes with malise to lower resistance to my slow spell.  I do NOT DOT any more except, or make any significant expenditure of mana except for the slow spell(which doesn't take much), unless in a situation that runs really sour, like when the mob seems to get maximum hits off on me every time, and I get off minimum hits, and so does my pet, or I pull two mobs by accident.  But that hardly ever, ever happens.  Generally, I cause ALL damage by melee, either from me or my pet.  And I'm far safer doing it than I was back when I had let my skills slip.  I'm generally down anywhere from a bubble of health to two bubbles at the end of a fight.  So I med a minute or two and go pull the next mob.  Pet doesn't need a heal, he's fine.<P>Now, this is extremely efficient, and doesn't call for uber items like the JBB bracer.  It seems I hardly ever sit still.  Was it efficient at first?  Heck, no.  The nay-sayers are right on that one.  But after all my skills built up and my natural AC got built up by taking punches, it has become extremely efficient.<P>So, the nay-sayers are right regarding efficiency and abilty to solo, for their situation, and I am right, for mine.  But mine used to be theirs.  I didn't want it to be, so I did the hard work, and now it isn't.<P>I asked myself how weak I wanted to be, and answered, well, not very.  And I went out and did something about it.<P>Along the way, I gradually swapped out more and more of my wisdom gear for pure AC gear.  For instance, I swapped out my runed mithril bracers (AC 4, wis 5, str 3) for rygorr bracers (AC 9).  I was down a lot of wisdom doing that, and that made me nervous.  But I came to realize that if I had built up enough natural AC, and added enough AC through tough armor, what exactly would I be using my wisdom for, or need it for?  Did I have enough mana without the wisdom bracers to root stray mobs, cast a heal(which I used to have memmed) or two, cast a few slows and DOTS in case the ones I cast failed to stick, and not be left without enough mana for a gate away from extreme danger, or some other need?  Did I still have enough mana for all that?  The answer was a clear yes.  Was I ever likely to really actually need all that mana anyway?  No.<P>That's because AC=mana, in a way -- in the situations I'm talking about.  If you get tough enough and have enough AC that you only need one DOT before the mob dies, not two, do you need the mana for that second DOT?  Same goes for heals.  If you need substantially less mana than you did before, it's also true that you need to wear fewer wisdom items.  They can then be replaced by items with better AC.  This will require still fewer heals on your part, requiring still less in the way of wisdom items.  My wisdom is varies from 120 to 148 when meleeing solo, and I am never in any real danger either way.<P>The trick is to recognize the point of diminishing marginal returns, as economists would say.  At what point do you have too little wisdom for the situation at hand, and at what point do you need to increase your AC gear?  Well, that depends on the mobs you are fighting, and the dangers of the zone.  Lots of wanderers?  You might need more wisdom to cast extra roots.  Very poor natural AC because you've been grouping and player a caster shaman too long?  You could well find soloing very inefficient and even dangerous until you shape up.  At a certain point, the extra AC or wisdom you get by wearing a certain piece of equipment will not be worth it, and only experimentation will show you where the balance lies for you individually.  Importantly, this IN TURN will change as your skills change, and sometimes dramatically.  This is what makes equipment decisions so complex -- it's based on variables that themselves change over time and depend on your situation.  <P>And therein is the rub -- NO question exists as to whether increased AC obtained through meleeing up your natural defense/AC is helpful; it's helpful no matter how high a level you get.<P>The real question I see is whether to go through the slower leveling that sometimes comes when you solo to build up these benefits.  You're not going to be getting the melee experience you need by grouping, and grouping in the right places will level you too quickly to keep you from dropping far behind in your melee skills.  So solo is the only realistic way to keep your melee skills/offense/defense high or maxed for your level.<P>Do you want to spend the time, and, yes, sometimes the boring time necessary to build up your solo ability?  If your armor pieces are presently too lousy to make you feel safe even trying it, are you willing to spend a week or so doing nothing but earning money, say, selling SOW potions, like I did, so you can buy something better?  Those are personal decisions.  <P>Frankly, my dramatic increases in AC gained by meleeing have made me a far, far tougher character than I used to be, beating even my most optimistic expectations, and made my decision a clear winner for me.  For the entire rest of my shaman career, I will enjoy those benefits.  Anybody I group with will also enjoy the benefits of having a shaman far less likely to die, as well.<P>They have also made me a very efficient solo artist far before level 49.  Are all shamans very efficient soloers?  Nope; it's something you have to earn, and you can't get it just by casting or having great armor or being twinked.  YOU MUST FIGHT.  And it's not enough to win; in a way, you must also lose--you must get hit a LOT.  As a matter of fact, doing things the usual way, leveling primarily via casting solo and/or in groups, will almost ensure that, while you can solo, it will not be all that efficient.  So for most people, soloing will be less of an option, and if they don't want to put the hard work in, maybe that's just fine for them.  <P>However, if you are willing to put the hard work in, the benefits will be there for you forever.  The natural AC you've built up will apply whether you are grouped or solo.  If a great weapon drops in your lap, you'll be able to use it right away, and to great effect.  (My two-hand blunt, for instance, used to be horrible, but now it's so good I put out so much damage I don't even need a shield.)  You'll still be just as good a caster as any casting shaman is, if you spend a few hours summoning food and practicing divination or firing off a few newbie evoc DD's at yourself or weenie mobs in a low level zone.  (Alteration takes care of itself, through cannibalize.)  That's important--you give up NOTHING by being a melee shaman while you're still young enough to do it without getting killed, and get enormous gains -- extreme efficiency, even pre-level 49, is certainly among them.  <P>Shamans played like casters too long, however, CANNOT EVER go back and get their melee skills back up, no matter how hard they try and how much they wish they had done things differently.  The mobs just get too tough, while you've gotten too weak.  Casting will be your way to go, and your only realistic option.  You can bet even a level 50 or 60 would be being dishonest if he said he didn't want 50 extra AC.  I can tell you for sure, though, that he doesn't want to get hit long enough by the mobs he's regularly fighting at that level to get it.<P>So being a melee shaman for a while by getting plenty of solo time in has no downsides, but fantastic upsides, while taking the typical easy way out that most shamans do has some unfortunate downsides -- poor weapons skills, poor offense, poor defense and therefore natural AC.<P>The only real consideration to me is time and fun factor.  Soloing can be boring and time consuming.  So you have to ask yourself how much the strength and survivability of your character is worth to you -- don't forget how much it's worth to the group.  A dead shaman often means a dead group.  How long do you want to take to develop your character fully?  I think I've been clear as to the benefits, and made clear that they're not merely theoretical, but come from my own personal experience, and I hope you can see how they would apply to yours.  However, I can't say anything helpful on what anyone might personally value, or how they like best to spend their time.  I can't argue that these benefits come without a cost to be paid -- in terms of a longer time taken to level, and possible boredom, and, until you get the hang of things and your abilities and natural defense/AC increase, an increased chance of dying if you're not careful.  <P>And if you hate soloing in the first place, nothing I've said above can matter.  Even if that's the case, though, you might find soloing less boring when your abilities are raised and you're constantly in action, and not medding.  And after a while, you'll find you level very quickly by soloing too.  Just not necessarily at first.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">  <BR>_____________________________________<BR>I also disagree that the pet is no good.  If he's dying every time, you're not using him right -- he's probably being used like a tank and not like a DOT.  He should be used, I think, in a way that makes sure he doesn't die--after you've dotted and/or debuffed, then slowed and/or meleed the mob enough so the mob hates your guts and will more or less ignore the pet.  If the mob starts paying more attention to the pet, move closer to the mob so he hits you preferentially.  If that still doesn't do it, fire off a blast or another DOT; that will almost always do it.  Then the pet acts like a DOT, which always works well for me.  I can fight for 10 hours without losing a pet, no problem.  If you can't seem to keep the pet from dying no matter what you do, fight the mob far away from the pet for a while, and only later drag him to the pet.
</FONT>
