<FONT SIZE="1" color="#000000" face="Verdana, Arial">
posted April 24, 2001 12:07 AM &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_profile&u=00006086" target=_blank>
<IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/profile.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Profile for Blarg"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://" target=_new><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/homepage.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Author's Homepage"></A> &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=private_message&u=00006086"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/priv_message.gif" BORDER='0' ALT="Send New Private Message"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=12&t=003038&reply_num=000027&u=00006086"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=12&t=003038&replyto=000027"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Well, I'm not saying AC is the answer to everything all the time; far from it.  I specifically noted that grouping is a different matter.  <P>I also noted that at the highest levels, you won't be able to be meleeing as much as you could even when you're solo -- the mobs just get too tough.  Their hitpoints get outrageous then, and they sometimes triple and quad-hit.  It's encouraging to hear good stories about people meleeing really high mobs, but I know you'll at least have to be much more selective as to which ones you can kill by primarily melee tactics, and your equipment had better be good.<P>But I continue to feel that it's exactly because the mobs have so many hitpoints and hit so hard and fast that higher levels are the worst time to start working on AC and weapons skills.  <P>You survive by a much thinner margin a lot of times.  It's when I'm taking quad-hits from monster mobs that I want my defense/AC ALREADY maxed.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> I don't want to begin the process of catching up then -- the mobs are so much tougher than the ones at lower level, that working on AC is much more dangerous then.  At level 30, I may be in some danger when I take double hits from mobs with low hitpoints if I'm not up to snuff, but at level 55, say, quad-hits can be a quick disaster to you, and a couple quick smacks from your friends on a mob's back won't solve the problem in a second or two and end the danger.  If casting our 51 slow is as big an aggro as everyone says, I'll be under a lot of pressure, and really want to be able to handle REAL tough mobs and not die, not be working my way toward it.  I love a margin of error.<P>I also found that it takes a LONG time -- a VERY long time, to work up skills and defense/offense once you've let them slip.  And while you do, you're in more danger than you would otherwise have to be.  I wasn't that far behind at 39, but even at the end of my hell level of 40, my offense and defense had a long way to go, as did my weapons skills.  Every level just put me five points further behind.  It took me till 43 to max my offense, and until 45, I think, to max my defense/AC.  That's six levels of near constant melee!  And I already had been meleeing more than most shamans I knew, and had pretty decent defense/AC and armor, both.  <P>I brought my 2h blunt up to 180, and my 1h blunt to 180, and piercing to 173, but my weapons max is 185 at my level.  I'm still quite far behind, considering how slowly increases come.  Sometimes I literally haven't gotten a single weapon skill or defense increase in five hours.  If 45 wasn't a hell level, I'd have no chance of maxing out all my weapons.  And then next level, of course, that part begins again.  Thank goodness my defense maxed out though!  It's SO much easier to survive now.<P>The thing is, if you max your defense at 55, versus maxing it at 45, you've gone ten whole levels with far less armor -- and survivability -- than you could have had.  And your group could have had, too.  That's a VERY long time to be weaker than you have to be, and right when you're starting to transition into much tougher mobs in scarier places.  <P>And if you die in the process?  Well, dying at lower levels is no fun, but post-50 it's a horror show.  It takes forever to make up that d*mn experience.  That's a huge reason I don't want to be worrying about my melee capabilities at that point.  While I may not need my weapons because I'm mostly casting while grouped in dungeons, I'll definitely want the defense/AC, because dying is awful then -- even with a rez, it stinks.  A death at 20 or 30 or 40 hardly slows me down, in comparison.  THAT's the time to take risks meleeing, or even to care about melee, because melee works very well then.  Also every level earlier that you get your defense up is a very nice gain you can enjoy for that much longer.  From seeing and talking to most of the shamans I bump into in the game, it's a benefit they usually don't have, but I'll bet it's one they'd want.<P>I love hearing stories about us being able to take a pounding at high levels, and want to do everything I can to prepare for that as quickly as possible.  Like I said in my other post, doing so has eliminated a LOT of my downtime, and taken me out of a lot of the danger I used to be in.  A lot of mobs actually don't do a whole lot to my health now, bringing me down maybe half a bubble.  Those guys would have murderized me if I had had to take that kind of abuse before working up both my weapons skills and defense/AC.<P>Now I can go off to face those uber mobs in my coming seasons with a great deal more confidence.  I don't expect I'll be meleeing in the future anywhere near as much as I can and do now, or even be able to. But, I am prepared to take a hit from mobs that one day perhaps I will have to use mostly casting to kill if solo, or that I couldn't solo at all.  Or, as prepared as I possibly can be, anyway.  <P>I'd rather have a shaman with 50 more AC in my group than a shaman without it.  Getting my AC up hasn't cost me a thing -- I can still put wisdom and mana armor on.  I can get my wisdom up to 205 if I want to with the equipment I have at this point, and I have a number of nice mana items too.  I still have all the casting potential of people who haven't worked on melee -- I just also have something extra -- the ability to take a much bigger hit and survive, and, thereby, help my whole group survive.  No small thing!<P>And if I want to run up and land a stun or a Blight Hammer DOT or whatever, I have the option to try it and land a blow, and land it for max damage, and take a hit while trying.<P>If I were in my 50's or mid 50's or late 40's and didn't have uber armor(which I don't) and a JBB(which I don't) or good defense/AC (which I DO) or good weapons skills(which I DO), I think I would probably just skip making the weapons better, with the possible exception of the spear on occasional solo jaunts (read: agonizingly SLOW improvement), and just concentrate on casting.  Frankly, I don't think my groups at high levels will want me meleeing anyway, they'll want me medding and slowing, etc. -- casting.  If I were behind in 2h blunt I doubt I'd bother fixing that by soloing endlessly, same with 1h blunt.  And I think I would miss out on fun that way, and the full variety and power of being a shaman, and, until I got the hell kicked outta me by super-strong mobs for the incredibly long time it takes to maximize defense/AC once you've fallen behind, I'd probably be a real fraidy cat, and have pigeon-holed myself into a corner.  I'd be notably weaker, and my group would be at least a bit weaker, too, because of me.  That all sounds like it s*cks to me.<P>So I'm not saying there's only one way to do it or one level range to do it in, or that you should wear the same AC or have the same considerations solo as you do when grouped, or wear the same stuff when you're weak as you do when strong.  I wore a lot more casting gear when weaker, for instance, because I had no choice -- I NEEDED to dot and cast much more at first.  I'm not even saying everyone has adequate physical armor pieces to even try building up melee like I'm talking about doing.  I did an awful lot of trading and making SOW potions before I could buy my armor and weapons, sometimes barely fighting for days and days on end.  If you're not willing to do that, I can sure understand that.  Bored the daylights outta me.  I don't really like trading.  I like killing stuff.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> <P>I'm just saying that there are really great benefits if you keep up your melee aspects as much as you possibly can, and that the longer you have your melee capabilities maxed, the longer you'll benefit from it.  (Conversely, the longer you wait, the more you'll be doing without.  Eventually you might be doing without permanently, on the weapons at least.)  I'm saying it's much harder to do practice melee at later levels, and much more dangerous, and the price for failure is FAR greater.  (My 54 druid knows something about dying in the 50's.)  I'm also saying you'll suffer more from not having those aspects of your character maxed at later levels than you will at lower levels, because life is tougher then, and mobs and situations less forgiving.<P>Therefore, catch-up, even when successful, is not really a great way to do it.  Doing it late is the hardest way to do it at the most dangerous time.  If you try, you probably won't try to do it with every weapon class, and will just forever abandon some.  Then when something great pops in your lap, there's every chance your average shaman will say it sucks if it's not a spear, and even encourage other shamans to feel the same way.  <P>I think this is probably the way most shamans go.  And I don't think it's a great way.  I think shamans can be tougher than some of the shamans I bump into are, and that it helps when you are.  I also think it's just plain old more fun to have as many options as possible.  If you have a choice between more options and fewer options, I can't see why fewer options is the way to go.<P>I could if melee really didn't work past 20, or 30, or 40 -- all of which I've heard shamans say!  And not just once.  I could justify abandoning options if 2h blunts really DID stink, and so did 1h blunts.  My own personal experience is that they do indeed stink -- if they're nowhere near their max for your level.  If they ARE good and high, then they don't stink at all.  So the options many (most? I don't know) shamans deny themselves seem good ones, and I wanted to say how good they've proven for me so far.<P>And even if you hate doing anything but casting and disagree with everything I've said, you just can't deny the value of 50 extra AC.  I made that for myself for free, just by meleeing.  I think it was a great choice.  I could have actually gotten that natural AC much earlier if I had learned the importance of melee earlier; I wish I had.<P>I never said it was always the most fun way to go, or that it was a very fast way to level.  <P>But as it is, I am going to go into my later levels in the best possible situation -- as tough as possible, with every one of my options fully open -- both for simple survival, and for fun.  I think that's worth a lot, and beats all the alternatives by a mile.
</FONT>
